Project: Finance¶

Exploratory Data Analysis
¶

Objective of the Proposed :¶

  • This Research Paper aims to analyze the data about Boston Housing and determine the person is capable for purchasing new home.

  • The main objective of this research work is to analyze and represent the various factors which have contributed in the Evolution of the Housing in the graphical format and perform a comparative study between the various factors.

  • To find the per capita crime rate by town in Boston on the Basis of proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.

  • To find the affected other factors like age of proportion of owner-occupied units built prioe to 1940,index of accessibility to radial highways,full-value property-tax rate per amount,school-college avaiablity.

2) Data Exploration¶

  • Import and read the dataset.
In [1]:
df.boston <-read.csv("/content/Boston.csv", header = TRUE)

Attributes Description:

Crim: per capita crime rate by town.

zn: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sqft.

indus: proportion of non-retail business acres per town.

chas: charles river dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)

nox: nitrogenoxide concentration (parts per 10 million)

rm: average number of rooms per dwelling.

age: proportion of owner occupied units built prior to 1940.

dis: weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centers.

rad: index of accessibility to radial highways.

tax: full value property-tax rate per $10000.

ptratio: student to teacher ratio by town.

black: 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.

lstat: lower status of the population(percent).

medv: median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

Project Report
¶

This report is created by the finance group members of Analytic Computing class

The objective of the our project is to help find the U.S census services concerning house in the area of the boston M.A. and factors that affect such as: crime_rate, industrial areas, age of house, taxes, percent of people having lower status and so on.

To start with, we selected our dataset from kaggle website and the imported the data using the read.csv into our data frame.

In the second step we did multiple data exploration such as: head(), tail() this prints the top 6 and bottom 6 lines of the data frame. Then after, we also printed the summary of the data frame which describes its overall structure starting with min value, max value as well as quartile range.

Thirdly, we did data cleaning on our dataset and removed the unnecessary columns like chas, concetration of nitrogenmonoxide, black. Then after, we took take of ther NA value by removing it and updated the new data frame.

The fourth step is Adpatation in which we estimated which two columns were related co-linearly. Then we calculated price of the house per room and the average distance to highway which shows the ease of access to transit.

Fifth steps was visualization. This is where most of the creative work is done to get insights on our data frame. We use density distribution graph to compare the relation between rooms per house with price of the house per room. Also plotted a scatter graph to demonstrate the positive correlation between the same variables as the density graph. Third plot was histogram represnting the how the vale of tax varied over time. Last but not the least 3D scater plot was also implemented into our data space, this plot shows the relation between Age, Industrial acres and Tax.

In the correlation section, we used library such as cormat to show as a summary as well as with heatmap how each of the selected column are correlated. Futher correlation was demonstrated with a scatter plot of proportion of owner occupied units built prior to 1940 against tax of the house and the output was what we predicted, a postive linear regression.

From this dataset we have selected median value of house as our response variable. Median value of house is our predictor value based on factors such as age of the house, tax, number of rooms, average distance to employment area as well the accessibilty to highway for easy transit, status of people also plays a major role as it is directly correlated with crime rate in the area. The reason for selecting this column as a response vairable was very straight forward as it was the column which could be used with multiple other variable to generate/predict the overall trend.

Eighth step is where we began to make linear regression models comparing the price of the house per room with lower status of population, non-retail industrial acres, property tax per $10000, student-to-teacher ratio and proportion of owner occupied units respectively. We use Adjusted r-sqaured we compare each of the model and from the output Model 1 was the best fit linear regression model with adjusted r-sqaured value of 0.485

In multi-linear regression, we are predicting the price of the house with the same factors as linear regression but combined/together unlike linear regression where we prdicted for individual factor. We created two models and out of which Model 2 was best fit with adjusted r-sqaured value of 0.536

Originality of the project - This dataset was not created by us rather it was imported from Kaggle "https://www.kaggle.com/code/prasadperera/the-boston-housing-dataset". We did not refer or copy anyones work from the internet. But, there might be some scenarios where we could have used the same variables to predict the similar output as others on the web and also could have used the same visualization to present our graphs. All the notebooks that we came across were coded in python language and none in r language hence different approach to dataset as the library used also differs to some extent. Although we reached to stack overflow and other multiple website for reference, this work solely belongs to us.
